    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-13T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-13T23:00:00-05:00" n="497"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/1678: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-14T11:00:00+07:00"
                            >December 14, 1943—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 14—7:37 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2404. Foreign Office informs us that, if it is agreeable to the American
                    Government, Dr. Soong wishes to sign in Chungking a reverse Lend-Lease agreement
                    in the terms of the draft note enclosed with the Department’s mail instruction
                    250, March 17, 1943 a copy of which (Department’s 637, May 19)<note n="62"
                        xml:id="d497fn62">Not printed, but see footnote 25, <ref target="#pg_537">p.
                            537</ref>.</note> was informally [handed] to Dr. Soong in Washington by
                    Mr. Acheson on May 15. I assume that my acknowledgement of such note should be
                    along the lines of enclosure No. 2 to the Department’s mail instruction under
                    reference with following phraseological changes: opening of second paragraph:
                    “In reply I am instructed by my Government to inform you”; and final substantive
                    paragraph: “This further integration …<note n="63" xml:id="d497fn63">Omission
                        indicated in the original.</note> gives great satisfaction to the Government
                    of the U.S.”</p>
                <p>While this gesture does not necessarily indicate that the Chinese Government
                    intends to implement the financial provision of the note in a manner
                    satisfactory to us, it at least lays the ground work for future discussions
                    which must ensue on that subject and for possible appropriate supplemental
                    agreements looking to the furnishing of desired financial services to our armed
                    forces and governmental establishments.</p>
                <p>Please instruct by telegraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
